{{no footnotes|date=February 2015}} The '''Early Opera Company''' is a British ensemble dedicated to the performance of [[baroque opera]]s using [[period instruments]]. It was founded in 1994 by Christian Curnyn. [[Handel]]'s operas feature prominently in its repertoire, and the Company has given notable performances of ''[[Agrippina (opera)|Agrippina]]'' in New York, ''[[Orlando (opera)|Orlando]]'' at the [[South Bank Centre]] Early Music Festival and ''[[Partenope]]'' at the [[Buxton Festival|Buxton]] and [[Aldeburgh Festival|Aldeburgh]] Festivals. They have also recorded ''Partenope'' and ''[[Semele (Handel)|Semele]]'' for the Chaconne label on [[Chandos Records]]. The recording of ''Semele'' was awarded the Handel Prize in 2008. Soloists who have performed with the company include [[Rosemary Joshua]], [[Hilary Summers]], [[Richard Croft (tenor)|Richard Croft]] and [[Gail Pearson]]. They performed at the [[Lufthansa Baroque Music Festival]] in May 2009 with [[John Eccles (composer)|John Eccles]]'s ''The Judgment of Paris'' in one its first ever performances. The ensemble also made the premiere recording of the work for [[Chandos Records]].
